title: THOR
body:
Underrated. It’s hard to remember what a huge jump and gamble the first Thor was at the time, and it never really got credit for it. Iron Man spends hours painstakingly watching a man build a metal suit that could definitely really happen in real life, honest. It’s post-Nolan. Thor opens by tossing Christopher Nolan into a giant gorge in the ancient realm of the frost giants, where men and women in huge helmets and capes scream and quip at each other while throwing enchanted weapons and casting illusions. Iron Man drove a car.

 So it’s a jump then, but it’s tethered. It doesn’t quite make the great leap into lunacy they’d make later, because it’s still early doors and we need things like audience surrogates and Stellan Skarsgard to explain everything. It’s a good job that Thor does the earth bits well too – the Marvel style still hasn’t solidified here yet, so instead of a hundred-mile quip-fest the New Mexico scenes play out like a sedate rom-com, wonkily but loveably edited and full of nice grace notes like Skarsgard getting drunk, ‘meow meow’ and Thor talking to Jane about science and magic. It’s delightful and grounding for a character that could have been a ridiculous mess.

 Once again it’s the actors that really sell it though, particularly Hiddleston. He’s fantastic here, treating the script as Shakespeare and imbuing every line with a seething jealousy and neediness that drag the character far out of his cackling comic book origins. He’s kind of the lead in the first two Thors; until Hemsworth really clicks in Ragnarok he simply overpowers everyone else, the sneering but wounded malevolence of the first Avengers his twatty peak. Hemsworth’s delightful too, just not as good as he will be; his ‘can I come home?’ after the first great Thor-Loki exchange is heartbreaking, positioning him as the big sweet kid of the Avengers who’ll lose everything come Infinity War. Oh, and Anthony Hopkins is in it too, and he screams BUTCHA NAT KING and HEYYYYYYY, which is nice.

 A mixed bag, it’s also full of incredible design work which the action direction never quite lives up to. Everything looks at bit Power Rangers, even if Loki and Thor’s battle on the rainbow bridge is full, glorious Kirby. The comic book stuff is a noble attempt at getting the wonder of decades of comic art up on screen that’ll be bettered later, while the hints to a larger universe are handled more deftly than Iron Man 2, with references to Banner, soon-to-be-dickbag SHIELD agents and grown men called Hawkeye all skipping in and out of the brotherly betrayal. It’s good. It’s loveable. Also all the Asgardians ride horses why don’t they do that anymore where did the horses go
